@jeyhunkarimov - with KIP-63 in, this PR becomes a little more complicated.  
We now have, and use, caching in the DSL. Stores that have caching enabled are wrapped with a `CachedStateStore`. This has a major implication  in that any Processors that are using a `CachedStateStore` no longer use `context.forward(..)` to forward values downstream. This is because values are instead sent downstream when items are flushed from the cache - this enables us to coalesce multiple updates to the same key into fewer downstream records. So if you have a look at say, `KStreamAggregateProcessor.init(...)`, you'll see:

```
 public void init(ProcessorContext context) {
            super.init(context);
            store = (KeyValueStore<K, T>) context.getStateStore(storeName);
            ((CachedStateStore) store).setFlushListener(new ForwardingCacheFlushListener<K, V>(context, sendOldValues));
        }
```

As you can see we expect the store to be a `CachedStateStore` and we are adding the listener that will forward values when a flush occurs. Now,  as this task is about adding custom state stores, we will no longer be able to assume that the store is a `CachedStateStore`. So, in all the `Processor`s where `CachedStateStore` is currently used we would need to know/check if we are indeed using a `CachedStateStore`, and we also need to save that information as we also need to know if we should call `context.forward(..)` in the `process` method. Again, if you look at `KStreamAggregateProcessor` you'll see that we don't call `context.forward(..)`

Additionally, we need to add a type argument to `StateStoreSupplier` as we have some processors that are expecting a `KeyValueStore` and others expecting a `WindowStore`.
The method signatures on `KGroupedStream` etc should become:

```
<W extends Window> KTable<Windowed<K>, V> reduce(final Reducer<V> reducer,
                                                      final Windows<W> windows,
                                                      final StateStoreSupplier<WindowStore> storeSupplier);

KTable<K, V> reduce(final Reducer<V> reducer,
                        final StateStoreSupplier<KeyValueStore> storeSupplier);
```

and so on.

Please let us know if you are happy to continue on with this or if you'd prefer someone else picked it up. Thanks for the help.

@mjsax @guozhangwang `StateDirectory.listTaskDirectories` returns all the directories that match the pattern of a task dir name. 

```
public File[] listTaskDirectories() {
        return stateDir.listFiles(new FileFilter() {
            @Override
            public boolean accept(final File pathname) {
                final String name = pathname.getName();
                return pathname.isDirectory() && name.matches("\\d+_\\d+");
            }
        });
    }
```

Even if you accessed the `StateDirectory` instance from each of the `StreamThread`s it still wouldn't help. Also, even if the `StateDirectory` instance for a `StreamThread` listed only the task directories currently owned by the `StreamThread` it still wouldn't help as at `cleanup` `KafkaStreams` is closed, so the `StreamThread`s have stopped and all the locks etc would have been released.

Hi @jeyhunkarimov - yes in `KStreamAggregateProcessor.init()` and other Processors, we will need to check first if the State Store is indeed an instance of `CachedStateStore`. If it is we can do the cast and set the Flush listener. If it isn't an instance of `CachedStateStore` we don't cast, so don't add the listener. Also, in process we need to know if this is a `CachedStateStore` or not as if it isn't cached, then we will also need to do `context.forward()`

So you could imagine something like this for a single processor:

```
 void init(ProcessorContext context) {
    store = (KeyValueStore<K, T>) context.getStateStore(storeName);
    if (store instanceof CachedStateStore) {
        cached = true;
        ((CachedStateStore) store).setFlushListener(new ForwardingCacheFlushListener<K, V>(context, sendOldValues));
    }

   void process(K key, V value) {
      // do whatever happens in the process
      store.put(key, value);
      if (!cached) {
         context.forward(...);
      }
   }
}
```

If you search for usages of `CachedStateStore.setFlushListener` you'll see about 7 usages of this in Processors. They will all need to be changed to adopt the same pattern, so it might be worth doing this a way that doesn't require the cast etc in every `Processor`, i.e, by passing in an Object that hides the details.

So yes -  a user should be able to provide any state store supplier whether it is cached or not and the processors should still work.

Does that help?

